article.headline: Georgia 80, Alabama A&M 36
article.story: ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Mike Mercer and Takais Brown scored 16 points apiece as Georgia routed Alabama A&M 80-36 Friday night. Jonathan Belt led Alabama A&M (3-3) with 14 points. The visitors managed just four field goals in the second half. After beating Valdosta State 105-74 and South Carolina State 105-60 in its last two games, Georgia (4-1) was attempting to reach the century mark for the third straight game for the first time in school history. It looked promising 36 seconds into the game when Georgia scored three baskets before A&M could even advance the ball past halfcourt. Georgia led 10-0 before A&M attempted a field goal, which was blocked by Georgia center Rashaad Singleton. The hometown Bulldogs were up 19-1 four minutes into the game after a 3-pointer by Levi Stukes. Trant Simpson finally scored a 3-point field goal for the visiting Bulldogs to make it 19-4 with 15:02 to go in the half. Midway through the first half, Georgia led 32-10, but A&M slowed down its attack. Often the visitors dribbled half of the 35-second shot clock away before initiating their offense. Georgia dominated A&M on the boards in the first half, 25-9, en route to a 47-20 lead at intermission. After hitting six of 10 3-pointers in the first half, Georgia came out in the second half trying to get the ball inside. Singleton foiled the plan, turning the ball over four times in Georgia's first seven possessions. For A&M, the second half started worse than the first. A&M did not score its first field goal until 7:58 left in the game when Belt hit a layup on a three-point play. By then it was 66-26. A&M's 36 points was the lowest total by a Georgia opponent since a 49-35 win over Mississippi State on Feb. 24, 1988.
